# Chaos Scheduler (MCP) usage

The **Chaos MCP server** (`chaos-scheduler`) exposes the local Chaos Scheduler's
REST API as MCP tools, resources, and prompts. Use it instead of shelling out or
hand-writing HTTP calls.

## When to use

- Registering, updating, or deleting scheduler workflows.
- Running or enqueueing a workflow on demand (one-off or event-driven).
- Reading run status, logs, results, and environment/queue state.
- Triaging a failed run.

## Tools (prefer these)

- **Read:** `list_environments`, `list_workflows`, `get_workflow`,
  `list_workflow_runs`, `get_run`, `get_run_logs`, `get_run_tasks`,
  `get_run_metrics`, `list_queues`, `list_queued_runs`, `list_email_profiles`,
  `get_version`, `health_check`.
- **Write:** `create_environment`, `register_workflow`, `update_workflow`,
  `set_workflow_spec`, `patch_workflow_spec`, `delete_workflow`,
  `run_workflow_now`, `enqueue_workflow`, `dispatch_workflow`,
  `rerun_workflow`, `create_email_profile`, `update_email_profile`,
  `delete_email_profile`, `set_workflow_email_profile`.

## Conventions

- **Use `enqueue_workflow` for manual runs.** Every manual run is
  admission-controlled — the scheduler manages concurrency/admission. There is no
  immediate/queue-bypass path: `run_workflow_now` is a **deprecated** alias that
  takes the same queued path and returns the same result, so prefer
  `enqueue_workflow`.
- **Always pass an `idempotency_key`** (a fresh UUID per logical action) to
  `enqueue_workflow` / `dispatch_workflow` / `rerun_workflow` (and the deprecated
  `run_workflow_now`). A reused key returns a duplicate response containing
  `status`, `run_id`, and `queued_run_id`; treat that as success, not a new run.
- **Inbound `dispatch_workflow` signing:** when the workflow has an inbound
  secret, pass `signature_secret` (canonical
  `METHOD\nPATH\nTIMESTAMP\nSHA256(body)` HMAC — the SDK sets
  `X-Chaos-Timestamp`, `X-Chaos-Event-Id`, `X-Chaos-Signature`). Optional
  `event_id` and `timestamp` pin replay fields. The configured inbound secret's
  value/status is unavailable through MCP.
- **Reading run detail.** `get_run` returns the run summary; use `get_run_logs`
  for stdout/stderr/exit, `get_run_tasks` for per-step tasks + retry attempts,
  and `get_run_metrics` for emitted metrics. Inspect queue pressure with
  `list_queues` (capacity/active/queued counts) and `list_queued_runs`.
- **Registration is authoritative:** workflows created via `register_workflow`
  are marked `managed_externally=true` (source-of-truth is external). Only change
  them through the API/MCP, not the UI. Registration is non-idempotent: read
  `chaos://workflows/index` first and update an existing workflow when possible.
- **Discover before authoring:** start with `chaos://authoring`, then load only
  the relevant `chaos://guides/*` and `chaos://schemas/*` resources. These are
  permissive `v1 stored_config` mirrors; backend validation and persistence
  normalization are authoritative.
- **Patch specs safely:** read `chaos://workflows/{id}/definition`, then prefer
  `patch_workflow_spec` for partial changes. Preserve `__redacted__` sentinels
  and use `set_workflow_spec` only for an intentional full replacement. Array
  sentinels need a unique id or unchanged webhook URL; identity changes need the
  real secret. Serialize concurrent writers because the patch tool is
  read-merge-write.
- **Environments are partitions.** Put a workflow in `production` (the default) unless the user asks for a sandbox/UAT workflow or a new environment.
- **Protected environments** (default `production`) reject workflow/environment
  writes unless the server was started with `--allow-protected-writes`. Global
  email-profile CRUD is environment-agnostic and relies on API scope/auth. The
  MCP default workflow target is `sandbox` — use that for integration tests and
  agent-driven registration.

## Reading state via @-references

Read-only state is available as resources for @-referencing:
`chaos://authoring`, `chaos://catalog`, `chaos://guides/*`,
`chaos://schemas/*`, `chaos://workflows/index`,
`chaos://workflows/{id}/definition`, `chaos://environments`,
`chaos://workflows`, `chaos://workflows/{id}`,
`chaos://workflows/{id}/runs`, `chaos://runs/{id}`, `chaos://runs/{id}/logs`,
`chaos://runs/{id}/tasks`, `chaos://runs/{id}/metrics`, `chaos://queues`,
`chaos://queued-runs`, `chaos://email-profiles`, `chaos://version`.

Workflow-ID templates offer prefix-filtered completions with MCP's native
100-value response cap and truthful pagination metadata. Template discovery
itself stays static and does not list backend records.

Definition resources always redact known secrets and report parse status.
Parsed stored configuration is not effective configuration or proof of runtime
enforcement.

## Prompts

Reusable templates: `triage_failed_run(run_id)`,
`summarize_workflow_health(environment)`, `register_workflow_for_repo(repo_path)`,
`safely_update_workflow(workflow_id)`.

## Failure triage loop

When a run fails: read it with `get_run` or `get_run_logs` (stderr tail),
inspect tasks via `get_run_tasks` only when step/retry detail is needed and
metrics via `get_run_metrics` only when measurements can explain the failure,
inspect the owning workflow with `get_workflow`, propose a concrete fix, and use
`rerun_workflow` with the failed source run plus a fresh `idempotency_key` only
if the failure looks transient and the operator explicitly confirms the retry.
